WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:19.280
Stage I The Witherd Arm by Thomas Hardy

00:19.280 --> 00:27.680
Chapter I The milkmaid and the wife

00:27.680 --> 00:39.960
It was six o'clock on a warm April evening, milking time for farmer lodges eighty cows.

00:39.960 --> 00:50.760
They stood quietly in the dairy, and the milkmaids were all at work.

00:50.760 --> 01:00.600
They say, Farmer Lodge is coming home with his new wife tomorrow, said one milkmaid.

01:00.600 --> 01:11.360
Yes, and she's young and pretty, I hear, a second girl said.

01:11.360 --> 01:17.760
She looked past her cow to the other end of the dairy.

01:17.760 --> 01:27.440
There was another milkmaid there, a thin, older woman, about thirty years old.

01:27.440 --> 01:31.160
The first girl looked at the older woman, too.

01:31.160 --> 01:35.440
I'm sorry for her.

01:35.440 --> 01:43.680
She said quietly to her friend, Oh no, said the second girl.

01:43.680 --> 01:47.840
That was years and years ago.

01:47.840 --> 01:55.680
Farmer Lodge never speaks to Rhoda Brook these days.

01:55.680 --> 02:03.480
When the milking was finished, the milkmaids left the dairy and went home.

02:03.480 --> 02:11.720
The thin woman, Rhoda Brook, did not walk to the village with the other girls.

02:11.720 --> 02:19.840
She went up the hill behind the farm to a little house near the trees.

02:19.840 --> 02:29.440
It was a poor house of only two rooms, and the roof did not keep the rain out.

02:29.440 --> 02:38.000
At the door of the house, the woman met her son, a boy of about twelve, and they went

02:38.000 --> 02:41.600
inside.

02:41.600 --> 02:49.200
I heard something at the dairy today, the woman said.

02:49.200 --> 02:54.520
Your father is bringing his young wife home tomorrow.

02:54.520 --> 02:58.920
I want you to go and look at her.

02:58.920 --> 03:03.520
Yes, mother, said the boy.

03:03.520 --> 03:06.760
His father married then?

03:06.840 --> 03:15.000
Yes, you can go into town and do my shopping for me.

03:15.000 --> 03:22.120
And when you see her, there, or on the road, look at her carefully.

03:22.120 --> 03:27.720
Yes, mother, what is she like?

03:27.720 --> 03:33.960
I want to know, is she tall, is she short?

03:33.960 --> 03:40.080
Are her eyes blue, or brown, or green?

03:40.080 --> 03:49.120
Look at the colour of her hair, the colour of her dress, and look at her hands.

03:49.120 --> 03:58.400
Does she have small, white hands, or the hands of a milkmaid, a worker's hands?

03:58.400 --> 04:02.800
You must look at all these things and tell me.

04:03.360 --> 04:08.400
Yes, mother, the boy said again.

04:08.400 --> 04:15.640
He took a piece of bread from the table and began to eat it.

04:15.640 --> 04:23.800
His mother said nothing more, but turned her thin, pale face to the open door.

04:23.800 --> 04:36.280
A beautiful, dark eyes stared out at the trees, seeing and not seeing.

04:36.280 --> 04:41.640
The next evening was warm and sunny.

04:41.640 --> 04:49.240
The road from the town to the farm went up and down a number of hills.

04:49.240 --> 04:56.680
Near the top of one big hill, the boy saw a carriage behind him.

04:56.680 --> 05:02.120
It was farm a lodge with his new wife.

05:02.120 --> 05:13.040
She was a pretty young thing, much younger than her husband, with a sweet, innocent face.

05:13.040 --> 05:20.880
The boy carried a heavy bag and was happy to stop and stare for a minute.

05:20.880 --> 05:29.000
The carriage came slowly up the hill, and the boy took a good, long look at the farmer's

05:29.000 --> 05:31.400
wife.

05:31.400 --> 05:36.360
His eyes never left her face.

05:36.360 --> 05:41.560
The farmer did not look at the boy once.

05:41.560 --> 05:48.880
And at the top of the hill, the carriage went faster, leaving the boy behind.

05:48.880 --> 05:56.480
How that poor boy stared at me, said the young wife.

05:56.480 --> 06:01.280
Yes, my love, I saw that.

06:01.280 --> 06:06.240
The farmer said, is he a boy from the village?

06:06.240 --> 06:13.800
No, I think he lives with his mother on one of these hills.

06:13.800 --> 06:22.400
He knows you then, of course, and everyone is going to stare at you at first, my pretty

06:22.400 --> 06:23.400
gertrude.

06:23.400 --> 06:30.320
Yes, I know, but that poor boy had a very heavy bag.

06:31.320 --> 06:35.760
Perhaps he wanted us to help him with the bag.

06:35.760 --> 06:43.360
Oh, these country boys can carry anything, said her husband.

06:43.360 --> 06:47.360
They do it all the time.

06:47.360 --> 06:51.280
The carriage went quickly on.

06:51.280 --> 06:59.200
After a time, the boy left the road and went up the hill to his mother's house.

06:59.200 --> 07:02.280
She was home before him.

07:02.280 --> 07:08.280
She took the heavy bag from him and began to take the things out.

07:08.280 --> 07:13.040
Well, did you see her?

07:13.040 --> 07:19.560
Yes, I had a good look at her on the road.

07:19.560 --> 07:22.680
And what is she like?

07:22.680 --> 07:24.200
She's nice.

07:24.200 --> 07:26.640
Is she young?

07:26.640 --> 07:30.400
Well, she's older than me.

07:30.400 --> 07:32.080
Of course she is.

07:32.080 --> 07:35.720
But is she older than me?

07:35.720 --> 07:41.320
No, she's younger.

07:41.320 --> 07:44.600
What color is her hair?

07:44.600 --> 07:51.640
It's a brown color, and her face is very pretty.

07:51.640 --> 07:54.080
Are her eyes dark?

07:54.160 --> 08:00.720
No, they're blue, and her mouth is very nice and red.

08:00.720 --> 08:05.120
And when she smiles, you can see white teeth.

08:05.120 --> 08:08.520
Is she tall?

08:08.520 --> 08:11.320
Said the woman, a little angrily.

08:11.320 --> 08:14.360
I couldn't see.

08:14.360 --> 08:17.840
She was in the carriage.

08:17.840 --> 08:21.520
Then tomorrow you must go to church.

08:21.520 --> 08:30.480
Go early, before she and Mr. Lodge arrive, and watch her when she walks in.

08:30.480 --> 08:35.320
Then come home and tell me.

08:35.320 --> 08:41.160
Very well, mother, but why don't you go and look at her?

08:41.160 --> 08:42.160
Never.

08:42.160 --> 08:46.160
I don't want to see her.

08:46.160 --> 08:50.480
She was with Mr. Lodge, of course.

08:50.480 --> 08:55.080
Would he look at you or speak to you?

08:55.080 --> 08:57.600
No.

08:57.600 --> 09:05.440
The next day the boy went to church and waited and watched.

09:05.440 --> 09:14.840
When Mr. and Mrs. Lodge arrived, everybody, not just the boy, stared at the new wife with

09:14.840 --> 09:17.880
interest.

09:17.880 --> 09:29.160
When the boy reached home, his mother said, well, she's not tall, she's short.

09:29.160 --> 09:40.960
The boy said, ah, said his mother, pleased, but she's very pretty, very.

09:40.960 --> 09:49.600
She had a beautiful white dress on, and it made a lot of noise when she moved.

09:49.600 --> 09:52.720
Mr. Lodge looked very happy with her.

09:52.720 --> 09:57.520
No more now, said the woman.

09:57.520 --> 10:02.880
You can tell me more later.

10:02.880 --> 10:12.080
In the next days, Rhoda Brook heard more and more from her son about the new wife.

10:12.080 --> 10:20.440
The boy often saw Mrs. Lodge around the farmhouse, but his mother never saw her, and never went

10:20.440 --> 10:24.280
near the farmhouse.

10:24.280 --> 10:30.080
At the dairy, the other milkmaids talked a lot about the new wife.

10:30.080 --> 10:37.800
They usually stopped when Rhoda was near, but she heard some of it.

10:37.800 --> 10:45.280
She remembered everything and forgot nothing.

10:45.280 --> 10:53.480
And slowly Rhoda Brook made a picture in her head of the young Mrs. Lodge, a picture as

10:53.480 --> 11:13.640
good, as true, as a photograph.

11:13.640 --> 11:19.000
Chapter 2 The Dream

11:19.000 --> 11:28.920
One night, two or three weeks later, when the boy was in bed, Rhoda Brook sat by the

11:28.920 --> 11:34.640
dying fire in her little house.

11:34.640 --> 11:43.560
She stared at the fire for a long time, but she saw only the picture in her head of the

11:43.560 --> 11:46.360
new wife.

11:46.360 --> 11:54.640
At last, tired from her day's work, she went to bed.

11:54.640 --> 12:01.040
But the picture of Gertrude Lodge did not go away.

12:01.040 --> 12:08.920
When Rhoda slept, the young wife was still there in Rhoda's dreams.

12:08.920 --> 12:16.840
She sat on Rhoda's body in the bed, staring into Rhoda's face.

12:16.840 --> 12:20.440
Her blue eyes were cold.

12:20.440 --> 12:27.400
And with a cruel laugh, she put her left hand in front of Rhoda's eyes.

12:27.400 --> 12:34.000
There, on the third finger, was her wedding ring.

12:34.000 --> 12:40.160
And the phantom of Gertrude Lodge laughed again.

12:40.160 --> 12:48.360
Rhoda turned this way and that way, but the phantom was still there.

12:48.360 --> 13:01.080
It sat heavier and heavier on Rhoda's body, and now Rhoda could not move.

13:01.520 --> 13:11.520
In her ears was that cruel laugh, and always in front of her eyes was that left hand with

13:11.520 --> 13:14.440
its wedding ring.

13:14.440 --> 13:24.120
At last, half dead with terror, Rhoda suddenly put out her right hand, took hold of the phantom's

13:24.120 --> 13:30.320
left arm, and pulled it hard.

13:30.320 --> 13:37.400
The phantom fell off the bed, onto the floor, and Rhoda sat up.

13:37.400 --> 13:50.320
Dear Gertrude, she cried, she felt cold, so cold, that was not a dream.

13:50.320 --> 13:52.560
She was here.

13:52.560 --> 14:02.040
She could still feel the young woman's arm under her hand, a warm, living arm.

14:02.040 --> 14:10.400
She looked on the floor for the woman's body, but there was nothing there.

14:10.400 --> 14:18.920
Rhoda Brooke slept no more that night, and at the dairy, early the next morning, she

14:18.920 --> 14:22.800
looked pale and ill.

14:22.800 --> 14:31.200
She could not forget the feel of that arm under her hand.

14:31.200 --> 14:38.760
When she came home for breakfast, her son asked her, what was that noise in your room

14:38.760 --> 14:41.400
last night, mother?

14:41.400 --> 14:44.760
Did you fall off the bed?

14:44.760 --> 14:46.760
Noise?

14:46.920 --> 14:50.360
Time did you hear it?

14:50.360 --> 14:53.320
About two o'clock.

14:53.320 --> 14:55.800
But what was it, mother?

14:55.800 --> 14:57.640
Something fell.

14:57.640 --> 14:59.760
I heard it.

14:59.760 --> 15:02.960
Was it you?

15:02.960 --> 15:06.040
Rhoda did not answer.

15:06.040 --> 15:12.160
And after breakfast, she began to do her work in the house.

15:12.240 --> 15:20.920
At about midday, she heard something and looked out of the window.

15:20.920 --> 15:29.600
At the bottom of the garden stood a woman, the woman from her dream.

15:29.600 --> 15:35.360
Rhoda stood still and stared.

15:35.360 --> 15:39.160
The boy came to look out of the window, too.

15:39.240 --> 15:42.960
Oh, there's Mrs. Lodge.

15:42.960 --> 15:48.600
He said, she told me, told you.

15:48.600 --> 15:50.560
Said his mother.

15:50.560 --> 15:52.440
She looked angry.

15:52.440 --> 15:56.160
Why did you speak to her?

15:56.160 --> 15:59.520
I told you not to.

15:59.520 --> 16:02.120
She spoke to me first.

16:02.120 --> 16:05.920
I met her in the road.

16:05.920 --> 16:08.560
When was this?

16:08.560 --> 16:10.880
Yesterday.

16:10.880 --> 16:13.880
What did you tell her?

16:13.880 --> 16:15.440
Nothing.

16:15.440 --> 16:21.280
She began to talk to me and then she saw my old shoes.

16:21.280 --> 16:25.480
She said, do they keep the rain out?

16:25.480 --> 16:33.960
And I said, no, they don't, but mother and I have no money for new shoes.

16:34.040 --> 16:39.560
Then she said, I can give you some better shoes.

16:39.560 --> 16:43.600
She's bringing them now, I think.

16:43.600 --> 16:46.440
Perhaps they're in her bag.

16:46.440 --> 16:49.360
She's very nice, mother.

16:49.360 --> 16:55.200
She gives things to lots of people.

16:55.200 --> 16:59.440
By now Mrs. Lodge was at the door.

16:59.440 --> 17:02.280
Rhoda wanted to run away.

17:02.360 --> 17:06.880
There was no back door in her little house.

17:06.880 --> 17:09.480
So she waited.

17:09.480 --> 17:13.280
And the boy ran to open the door.

17:13.280 --> 17:16.920
This is the right house, then.

17:16.920 --> 17:20.520
Said Mrs. Lodge, smiling at the boy.

17:20.520 --> 17:25.360
And this is your mother, is it?

17:25.360 --> 17:32.240
The face and body were the same as those of the Phantom in Rhoda's dream.

17:32.240 --> 17:37.040
But there was nothing cruel in this face.

17:37.040 --> 17:46.000
The blue eyes were warm and the smile was sweet and kind.

17:46.000 --> 17:54.040
The young woman took the shoes out of her bag and gave them to the boy.

17:54.040 --> 18:00.640
She smiled and talked in a warm and friendly way.

18:00.640 --> 18:05.520
How kind she is, thought Rhoda.

18:05.520 --> 18:10.640
How young and sweet and innocent.

18:10.640 --> 18:15.160
Why did I have that bad dream about her?

18:15.160 --> 18:22.520
She's a friend, not an enemy.

18:22.520 --> 18:30.120
Two days later Mrs. Lodge came again with a new shirt for the boy.

18:30.120 --> 18:37.080
And twelve days after that she visited Rhoda a third time.

18:37.080 --> 18:41.680
The boy was out that day.

18:41.680 --> 18:45.720
I like walking up here on the hill.

18:45.720 --> 18:54.160
Mrs. Lodge told Rhoda, and your house is the only one up here.

18:54.160 --> 18:59.480
They talked about the weather and the village.

18:59.480 --> 19:03.120
Then Mrs. Lodge got up to leave.

19:03.120 --> 19:07.520
Are you well, Rhoda?

19:07.520 --> 19:08.520
She asked.

19:08.520 --> 19:11.440
You look pale.

19:11.440 --> 19:16.520
Oh, I'm always pale.

19:16.520 --> 19:18.000
Said Rhoda.

19:18.000 --> 19:22.480
But what about you, Mrs. Lodge?

19:22.480 --> 19:24.840
Are you well?

19:24.840 --> 19:28.280
Yes, I am.

19:29.280 --> 19:31.280
There is something.

19:31.280 --> 19:34.280
It's nothing very bad.

19:34.280 --> 19:38.280
But I don't understand it.

19:38.280 --> 19:42.280
She uncovered her left hand and arm.

19:42.280 --> 19:46.280
There were marks on the arm.

19:46.280 --> 19:49.280
Yellowy brown marks.

19:49.280 --> 19:53.280
Like marks made by fingers.

19:53.280 --> 19:57.280
Rhoda stared at them.

19:57.280 --> 20:00.000
How did it happen?

20:00.000 --> 20:01.000
She asked.

20:01.000 --> 20:04.480
I don't know.

20:04.480 --> 20:06.600
Said Mrs. Lodge.

20:06.600 --> 20:12.560
One night when I was in bed I had a dream.

20:12.560 --> 20:18.360
And then suddenly my arm hurt very badly.

20:18.360 --> 20:22.400
Perhaps I hit it on something in the daytime.

20:22.400 --> 20:25.760
But I don't remember it.

20:25.760 --> 20:27.640
She laughed.

20:27.640 --> 20:32.200
My dear husband says it's nothing very much.

20:32.200 --> 20:35.280
And he's right, of course.

20:35.280 --> 20:37.280
Yes.

20:37.280 --> 20:41.960
Which night was that?

20:41.960 --> 20:44.200
Said Rhoda.

20:44.200 --> 20:47.880
Mrs. Lodge thought for a moment.

20:47.880 --> 20:51.760
It was two weeks ago today.

20:51.760 --> 20:54.640
It was two o'clock in the night.

20:54.640 --> 21:00.000
I remember because I heard the clock.

21:00.000 --> 21:09.000
It was the same night, the same hour as Rhoda's dream of the Phantom.

21:09.000 --> 21:13.160
Rhoda remembered the terror of it and felt cold.

21:13.160 --> 21:17.000
How can this be?

21:17.000 --> 21:20.760
She thought when Mrs. Lodge left.

21:20.760 --> 21:22.760
And I do that?

21:22.760 --> 21:25.560
But why?

21:25.560 --> 21:28.440
She is innocent and kind.

21:28.440 --> 21:32.520
I don't want to hurt her.

21:32.520 --> 21:36.520
And how can a thing like that happen?

21:36.520 --> 21:43.720
Only witches can do things like that.

21:43.720 --> 22:05.320
Chapter 3 The Face in the Glass

22:05.320 --> 22:08.480
The days went past.

22:08.480 --> 22:14.680
And Rhoda Brooke was afraid to meet Mrs. Lodge again.

22:14.680 --> 22:22.920
She liked her and did not want to remember the strange dream or the strange marks on

22:22.920 --> 22:26.480
the young wife's arm.

22:26.480 --> 22:32.560
But she could not stop thinking about them.

22:32.560 --> 22:38.040
One day they met on the road from the village.

22:38.040 --> 22:41.000
They began to talk.

22:41.000 --> 22:49.560
And after a minute or two Rhoda said, How is your arm Mrs. Lodge?

22:49.560 --> 22:52.720
Is it better now?

22:52.720 --> 22:56.120
No, it isn't.

22:56.120 --> 22:59.200
It's worse than before.

22:59.200 --> 23:02.040
Sometimes it hurts very badly.

23:02.040 --> 23:07.000
What does the doctor say about it?

23:07.000 --> 23:09.840
Ask Rhoda.

23:09.840 --> 23:12.800
He doesn't understand it.

23:12.800 --> 23:20.240
He just says, Put the arm in hot water for five minutes, twice a day.

23:20.240 --> 23:27.680
Well, I do that, but it doesn't help.

23:27.680 --> 23:31.520
Can I look at your arm?

23:31.520 --> 23:33.760
Ask Rhoda.

23:33.760 --> 23:39.480
Once again the younger woman uncovered her arm.

23:39.480 --> 23:43.000
And Rhoda stared at it.

23:43.000 --> 23:49.200
The arm was thinner and a little withered.

23:49.200 --> 23:58.480
And the marks looked more and more like marks made by fingers.

23:58.480 --> 24:02.080
Rhoda remembered her dream.

24:02.080 --> 24:09.640
And the feel of the arm under her hand in just the same place.

24:09.640 --> 24:16.000
It looks like the marks of fingers, Gertrude Lodge said.

24:16.000 --> 24:18.720
She tried to laugh.

24:18.720 --> 24:28.640
My husband says they are a witch's marks, a witch put her hand on my arm, he says.

24:28.640 --> 24:31.480
And it's killing the flesh.

24:31.480 --> 24:37.080
No, no, said Rhoda quickly.

24:37.080 --> 24:40.720
She felt cold and afraid.

24:40.720 --> 24:47.000
Don't listen to those old stories.

24:47.000 --> 24:49.920
The young wife's face was unhappy.

24:49.920 --> 24:57.360
No, but you see, I think he begins to...

24:57.360 --> 25:03.960
And love me less because of these marks on my arm.

25:03.960 --> 25:10.440
Men always like their wives to be pretty, don't they?

25:10.440 --> 25:19.840
Some men do, said Rhoda, but don't show him the arm, cover it all the time.

25:19.840 --> 25:23.520
And then he can't see it.

25:24.520 --> 25:29.920
But he knows the marks are there.

25:29.920 --> 25:38.720
Gertrude looked away, but Rhoda could see the tears in her eyes.

25:38.720 --> 25:47.120
I hope your arm is better soon, Mrs. Lodge, she said quietly.

25:47.120 --> 25:52.320
She said goodbye and began to walk home.

25:52.320 --> 26:00.400
She felt sorry for the poor, innocent young wife and did not want to hurt her.

26:00.400 --> 26:05.200
But she did not feel sorry for the husband.

26:05.200 --> 26:10.080
She walked home, thinking about him.

26:10.080 --> 26:20.160
So, farmer Lodge, she thought, you loved me once but then you left me

26:20.160 --> 26:22.960
and did nothing to help me.

26:22.960 --> 26:29.520
You wanted a new, younger and prettier woman for your wife.

26:29.520 --> 26:37.920
But she is not so pretty now, is she?

26:37.920 --> 26:47.200
The next day, Rhoda walked home from the dairy after evening milking at the usual time.

26:47.280 --> 26:54.960
She was nearly at her house when she saw Gertrude Lodge behind her.

26:54.960 --> 26:59.120
Rhoda went down the hill to meet her.

26:59.120 --> 27:01.920
Oh, Rhoda!

27:01.920 --> 27:08.720
Called Gertrude, I wanted to see you, to ask you.

27:08.720 --> 27:15.440
Her face was pale and worried, and she held her left arm with her other hand.

27:17.600 --> 27:23.600
Somebody told me, she said, about a man at Eggedon Heath.

27:25.200 --> 27:32.720
They don't know his name, but they say he is a famous wise man and can help people with

27:32.880 --> 27:36.400
with things like this.

27:38.560 --> 27:45.040
She looked down at her left arm and then looked at Rhoda with hope in her eyes.

27:47.600 --> 27:51.440
They say, you know about him, this wise man.

27:52.960 --> 27:54.240
Do you know his name?

27:55.280 --> 27:58.000
Perhaps they mean Mr. Trendel.

27:58.960 --> 28:02.720
Rhoda said, slowly, she felt ill.

28:04.480 --> 28:10.000
This man, Trendel, people said, could do many strange things.

28:11.680 --> 28:13.680
He could understand dreams.

28:15.360 --> 28:18.400
He could drive phantoms out of houses.

28:19.600 --> 28:22.400
He could stop the work of witches.

28:23.280 --> 28:27.520
I am not a witch, she thought.

28:28.400 --> 28:29.600
I am not!

28:30.800 --> 28:33.520
I do not believe in these things.

28:36.720 --> 28:37.920
Dertrude watched her.

28:39.840 --> 28:42.160
You know him, she said.

28:43.600 --> 28:45.440
I can see it in your face.

28:47.040 --> 28:50.640
Of course, I don't believe in wise men.

28:51.520 --> 28:52.800
What can they do?

28:53.760 --> 28:58.640
But, well, I can just go and see him.

28:59.920 --> 29:01.760
Is it far to his house?

29:03.760 --> 29:07.200
Yes, about five miles.

29:08.720 --> 29:09.440
Said Rhoda.

29:11.040 --> 29:13.040
Well, I must walk there.

29:14.720 --> 29:17.040
I cannot tell my husband about this.

29:17.040 --> 29:22.480
Can you come with me, Rhoda, to show me the way?

29:24.000 --> 29:25.600
Perhaps tomorrow afternoon?

29:27.200 --> 29:28.640
Oh, no, it's...

29:29.600 --> 29:29.840
I...

29:31.040 --> 29:31.840
Rhoda began.

29:32.720 --> 29:35.360
Please, said Gertrude.

29:37.360 --> 29:40.720
And in the end, Rhoda could not say no.

29:42.000 --> 29:44.800
Mrs. Lodge was good and kind.

29:45.760 --> 29:47.680
And she needed a friend's help.

29:49.760 --> 29:54.480
But perhaps a wise man could see into people's dreams.

29:56.560 --> 29:59.920
Rhoda did not want to meet this man, Trendel.

30:01.120 --> 30:02.640
And she was afraid.

30:06.880 --> 30:11.920
The next afternoon, she met Gertrude by the trees near her house.

30:12.720 --> 30:18.000
And they began the long walk across the hills to Eggedon Heath.

30:20.400 --> 30:27.760
It was a cold day, and the sky above the hills was dark and unfriendly.

30:29.040 --> 30:32.720
They found Mr. Trendel's house outside the village.

30:34.080 --> 30:36.480
He was at home when they arrived.

30:38.160 --> 30:41.120
He was an old man with gray hair.

30:42.400 --> 30:46.720
And he looked long and hard at Rhoda when he saw her.

30:48.960 --> 30:51.680
Mrs. Lodge told him about her arm.

30:53.040 --> 30:54.800
And he looked at it carefully.

30:56.160 --> 31:01.440
No, doctors can't do anything for this.

31:02.720 --> 31:08.000
He said, this is the work of an enemy.

31:08.640 --> 31:11.200
Rhoda moved away a little.

31:12.320 --> 31:13.120
An enemy?

31:13.600 --> 31:15.040
What enemy?

31:15.680 --> 31:17.440
Asked Mrs. Lodge.

31:18.400 --> 31:20.080
I don't know.

31:21.120 --> 31:23.360
Said the wise man looking at her.

31:24.160 --> 31:26.560
But perhaps you do.

31:28.080 --> 31:31.040
I can show the person to you.

31:32.240 --> 31:34.320
Do you want me to do that?

31:34.400 --> 31:36.320
Yes, said Gertrude.

31:37.440 --> 31:41.280
Yes, please show me.

31:44.000 --> 31:47.120
Mr. Trendel took Gertrude into another room.

31:48.560 --> 31:53.360
But the door was open and Rhoda could see into the room.

31:55.360 --> 32:00.400
The wise man took an egg and did something to it.

32:00.720 --> 32:09.120
Then he put a glass of water on the table and carefully broke the egg open.

32:10.880 --> 32:15.120
The white of the egg went down into the water,

32:16.640 --> 32:23.520
changing to a milky white color and moving slowly round and round.

32:26.000 --> 32:29.120
He put the glass in front of Gertrude.

32:31.280 --> 32:35.120
Look down into the water.

32:36.320 --> 32:39.200
He said, look for a face.

32:41.840 --> 32:44.160
Gertrude stared down into the water.

32:45.520 --> 32:48.000
Do you see a face?

32:49.600 --> 32:51.600
The wise man asked quietly.

32:54.320 --> 32:58.320
Gertrude whispered something, but Rhoda could not hear.

32:58.400 --> 33:01.840
She turned away from the door.

33:03.040 --> 33:06.400
When Mrs. Lodge came out, her face was pale,

33:07.600 --> 33:08.960
paler than Rhoda's.

33:10.960 --> 33:16.960
Mr. Trendel closed the door behind her and the two women began to walk home.

33:19.760 --> 33:22.080
But things were not the same between them.

33:22.080 --> 33:28.240
Did he ask for money?

33:29.520 --> 33:30.720
Rhoda said quietly.

33:32.000 --> 33:33.440
Oh no, nothing.

33:35.200 --> 33:38.720
He did not want a penny, said Gertrude.

33:40.400 --> 33:42.080
And what did you see?

33:43.440 --> 33:44.240
Asked Rhoda.

33:45.760 --> 33:46.160
Nothing.

33:47.920 --> 33:49.520
I don't want to speak about it.

33:52.160 --> 33:54.400
Gertrude did not look at Rhoda.

33:56.480 --> 34:04.800
Her pretty young face looked ten years older and was now more like the face of the phantom

34:04.800 --> 34:05.840
in Rhoda's dream.

34:07.680 --> 34:10.320
They did not speak for a long time.

34:11.760 --> 34:14.160
Then Gertrude said suddenly,

34:14.800 --> 34:20.640
Did you want me to come here and see this wise man?

34:21.920 --> 34:23.200
How strange of you.

34:24.560 --> 34:30.240
No, I didn't, but now I am not sorry we came.

34:33.040 --> 34:35.280
For the first time since her dream,

34:36.000 --> 34:38.080
Rhoda felt a little pleased.

34:39.680 --> 34:42.880
Life was cruel, she thought.

34:44.160 --> 34:47.840
And Gertrude Lodge must learn that lesson too.

34:50.880 --> 34:57.200
On the long walk home, they did not speak again about their visit to the wise man.

34:58.880 --> 35:05.840
But other people did and whispered stories about it in all the farms and dairies.

35:08.240 --> 35:12.800
Mrs. Lodge could no longer use her withered arm to do anything.

35:14.240 --> 35:20.720
And people began to put the word witch in front of the name Rhoda Brooke.

35:23.120 --> 35:27.760
Rhoda said nothing to anybody about the phantom of her dream.

35:29.120 --> 35:32.000
But her face got thinner and paler.

35:33.760 --> 35:42.640
And in the spring she and her boy left their house and went away into the hills in the west.

35:44.160 --> 35:59.040
Chapter 4

36:00.000 --> 36:01.680
The Cure for a Curse

36:03.600 --> 36:10.320
Six years went past, and Mr. and Mrs. Lodge's married life was not happy.

36:10.560 --> 36:15.920
The farmer said little and did not often smile.

36:17.440 --> 36:25.040
His wife had a withered arm and there were no children to call him father and to run laughing

36:25.040 --> 36:33.600
around the farmhouse. He thought of Rhoda Brooke and her son, his son.

36:35.200 --> 36:39.600
But that was the past and he could not change it now.

36:41.200 --> 36:50.080
Gertrude Lodge was a different woman too. She was only 25 but she looked older.

36:51.600 --> 36:58.320
Once a happy smiling woman she was now sad and worried all the time.

37:00.320 --> 37:06.960
She loved her husband but he no longer loved her and she knew it.

37:07.840 --> 37:17.760
Six years of married life and only a few months of love she sometimes whispered.

37:19.120 --> 37:28.480
Her left arm was no better. She tried one thing after another but nothing helped it.

37:30.000 --> 37:35.600
Some of the things were a little strange and her husband did not like them.

37:37.360 --> 37:44.640
You think too much about your arm. He said, you need somebody to talk to,

37:45.760 --> 37:51.360
somebody to be around the house. At one time there was a boy.

37:52.880 --> 38:03.280
I wanted him to come and live with us. But he is too old now and he went away. I don't know where.

38:06.960 --> 38:12.640
Gertrude knew about this boy now and all of Rhoda Brooke's story.

38:13.920 --> 38:17.520
But she and her husband never spoke about it.

38:19.520 --> 38:26.080
And she never said anything to him about her visit to the wise man of Eggedon Heath

38:27.440 --> 38:30.080
or about the face in the glass.

38:30.880 --> 38:36.960
She wanted so much to find a cure for her arm.

38:38.240 --> 38:43.920
My husband cannot love me because of this arm, she thought.

38:45.600 --> 38:49.280
So I must find a cure for it. I must.

38:51.120 --> 38:57.440
The wise man helped me before. Perhaps he can help me again.

39:00.720 --> 39:04.800
So one day she walked to Eggedon Heath.

39:07.440 --> 39:13.120
She did not know the way. But at last she found the house.

39:16.640 --> 39:22.160
You can send away other things I know. She said to Trendall.

39:22.960 --> 39:31.200
Hair on women's faces and things like that. Why can't you send this away?

39:33.200 --> 39:35.680
She uncovered her poor withered arm.

39:37.920 --> 39:42.640
No, I'm sorry, but I can't help you.

39:43.520 --> 39:49.920
Said Trendall, your arm is withered because of a curse.

39:50.880 --> 39:54.320
It's not easy to find a cure for that.

39:56.560 --> 40:02.160
Is there no cure anywhere? asked Gertrude sadly.

40:04.400 --> 40:10.240
There is one thing. Trendall began slowly.

40:11.200 --> 40:15.120
But it's not easy for a woman to do.

40:16.560 --> 40:21.200
Oh, tell me. Said Gertrude, please.

40:23.360 --> 40:29.680
You must put the withered arm on the neck of a hanged man.

40:30.560 --> 40:38.800
You must do it before he's cold. Just after they take his body down.

40:40.880 --> 40:43.920
Gertrude's face was pale.

40:46.560 --> 40:47.840
How can that do good?

40:49.520 --> 40:55.840
It can turn the blood and that changes many things in the body.

40:57.360 --> 41:05.840
You must go to the jail when they hang someone and wait for the body when they bring it in.

41:06.480 --> 41:19.920
In the old days, lots of people did it. These days, not so many do it, but it is still the best cure for a curse.

41:23.280 --> 41:27.600
Back at home, Gertrude thought about this for a long time.

41:28.960 --> 41:33.600
She tried to forget it, but she couldn't.

41:34.480 --> 41:41.520
She wanted to be pretty again. She wanted her husband to love her again.

41:43.040 --> 41:48.080
Yes, she must try this cure. She must.

41:49.520 --> 41:52.960
But how do I do it? She thought.

41:54.160 --> 41:56.320
Where is the nearest jail?

41:57.760 --> 41:59.760
How can I get there?

42:00.400 --> 42:03.440
How often do they hang people?

42:04.880 --> 42:12.080
And when there is a hanging, how can I learn about it before it happens?

42:14.400 --> 42:15.920
So many questions.

42:17.680 --> 42:23.600
There was no one to help her, but slowly she began to find the answers.

42:25.600 --> 42:28.400
She asked careful questions in the village.

42:29.760 --> 42:33.120
Because country people always know everything.

42:35.760 --> 42:37.680
One old man was very helpful.

42:39.680 --> 42:48.800
The nearest jail is a caster bridge, 15 miles away. He told Gertrude.

42:50.000 --> 42:59.280
They have trials there every three months, and there's usually a hanging after the trials.

43:00.560 --> 43:10.880
Some poor man or boy takes a cow or a sheep or just some bread, and they hang him for it.

43:12.080 --> 43:16.560
Lots of people go to watch the hangings. I don't know why.

43:19.120 --> 43:22.240
The next trials were in July, Gertrude learned.

43:23.760 --> 43:28.640
She asked her husband about them, but Lodge said very little,

43:30.560 --> 43:35.440
he was colder to her than usual, and she did not ask him again.

43:37.120 --> 43:42.000
He was often away these days, so she did not see much of him.

43:44.240 --> 43:50.000
July came, and Gertrude went to see the helpful old man in the village again.

43:50.640 --> 43:58.080
Just one hanging this time, he told her, it's for arson, I think.

43:58.800 --> 44:01.760
They're going to hang him next Saturday.

44:04.480 --> 44:06.240
Gertrude walked slowly home.

44:08.240 --> 44:14.560
I cannot tell my husband about this, this cure, she thought.

44:15.520 --> 44:20.320
And how can I be away from home for two nights?

44:21.840 --> 44:23.440
What can I say to him?

44:25.360 --> 44:27.600
But in the end, it was easy.

44:29.360 --> 44:33.120
On the Thursday before the hanging, Lodge came to her.

44:35.520 --> 44:38.560
I'm going away for three nights.

44:39.440 --> 44:45.040
He said, it's about farm work, so you can't come with me.

44:46.800 --> 44:50.480
That's all right, Gertrude said quietly.

44:51.600 --> 44:53.680
I'm happy to stay at home.

44:55.920 --> 44:57.360
They said nothing more.

44:58.800 --> 45:02.960
And on Thursday, Lodge drove away in the carriage.

45:09.520 --> 45:25.440
Chapter 5, The Hangman

45:28.080 --> 45:32.560
The next morning, Gertrude got ready to leave the caster bridge.

45:32.560 --> 45:41.280
She did not want to go by road, because she did not want to meet any of her husband's friends.

45:43.200 --> 45:49.840
So she took one of the heavy horses from the farm and rode west across the hills.

45:52.320 --> 46:01.360
She was afraid of riding with a half-dead arm, but the farmhorse was quiet and slow and easy to ride.

46:03.360 --> 46:12.560
He carried her uphill and downhill, past rivers and through trees, moving west all the time.

46:15.040 --> 46:17.760
The sun slowly went down in the sky.

46:19.520 --> 46:26.240
And it was nearly eight o'clock when Gertrude stopped for a moment at the top of a hill.

46:27.040 --> 46:36.240
It was the last hill before the town, and she could see the roofs of caster bridge below.

46:38.560 --> 46:44.800
There was a big building on a hill at the end of the town with a white roof.

46:46.880 --> 46:54.000
She knew this was the jail, and she could see a lot of workmen on the roof.

46:56.320 --> 47:03.040
What are they doing? She thought. They're building something up there on the roof.

47:04.480 --> 47:14.960
Oh! Suddenly she understood and quickly turned her eyes away. It was a warm summer evening,

47:15.840 --> 47:17.520
but she shivered with cold.

47:17.840 --> 47:27.360
Tomorrow they're going to hang a man on that roof. She thought, and when he is dead,

47:28.960 --> 47:37.440
she shivered again. But then she remembered her husband's cold words and his unsmiling face,

47:39.200 --> 47:45.840
and she rode on down into the town. She found a room to stay for the night,

47:46.800 --> 47:48.960
and then went out into the town.

47:50.960 --> 47:53.680
What do I do now? She thought.

47:54.880 --> 47:57.360
How can I get into the jail tomorrow?

47:59.120 --> 48:04.640
Who must I talk to? The men at the jail? Or the hangman?

48:07.840 --> 48:12.880
She was afraid to go to the jail, so she went to find the hangman.

48:13.760 --> 48:19.120
He had a house down by the river, a boy in the town told her.

48:20.800 --> 48:29.040
When she found the house, she stood outside for some minutes, afraid to go to the door.

48:30.240 --> 48:34.960
Then the door opened, and a man came out.

48:35.280 --> 48:41.280
Who are you? He called out. What do you want?

48:43.520 --> 48:45.680
I want to speak to you for a minute.

48:47.840 --> 48:50.000
He came nearer and looked at her.

48:51.280 --> 48:58.960
Well, well, that's a pretty face, he said. Come into the house.

48:59.600 --> 49:02.640
They went inside.

49:04.240 --> 49:12.480
Davis, that was his name, was a hangman on some days, but a gardener on other days.

49:14.640 --> 49:16.720
Is it about gardening work?

49:18.800 --> 49:25.040
He asked Gertrude. I can't do any tomorrow, because I'm working at the jail.

49:25.840 --> 49:30.720
Yes. Yes, I know. That's why I'm here.

49:32.080 --> 49:37.120
Ah, I thought so. Is the poor man one of your family, then?

49:38.000 --> 49:39.840
Perhaps your young brother?

49:41.280 --> 49:45.200
No. Davis looked at Gertrude's dress.

49:46.720 --> 49:52.400
I don't think so. Was he one of your farm workers, perhaps?

49:53.280 --> 49:56.800
No. What time is the hanging?

49:58.240 --> 50:01.120
The same as usual. Twelve o'clock.

50:02.960 --> 50:07.920
And it is. It is going to happen. Yes?

50:09.120 --> 50:12.480
Oh, yes. Nothing can stop the hanging now.

50:13.600 --> 50:19.440
Said Davis. But I'm sorry for this young man. I truly am.

50:20.320 --> 50:26.240
He's only eighteen. They say it was arson, but I don't know.

50:27.280 --> 50:32.960
He was there when the fire began, but there were twenty other men there too.

50:33.520 --> 50:38.880
So how do they know? I think they just want to hang someone, anyone.

50:40.160 --> 50:42.560
But what can I do for you, my pretty?

50:43.120 --> 50:49.440
I need a cure, Gertrude said. A cure for a curse.

50:50.000 --> 50:55.440
And a wise man told me about the hanged man, and...

50:56.400 --> 50:59.200
And turning the blood.

51:00.320 --> 51:04.560
Oh, yes, Miss. Now I understand.

51:04.560 --> 51:10.720
People sometimes come for that. But not pretty young things like you.

51:11.200 --> 51:15.840
Well, well. What's the cure for?

51:17.680 --> 51:18.240
It's this.

51:20.240 --> 51:22.240
Gertrude uncovered her left arm.

51:25.760 --> 51:30.400
It's all withered. Said the hanged man, looking at it.

51:31.920 --> 51:33.440
Yes, she said.

51:34.320 --> 51:40.720
Well, a hanged man's neck is the best cure for that, he said.

51:41.680 --> 51:43.680
Your wise man was right.

51:45.520 --> 51:50.000
So, can you help me? Gertrude whispered.

51:51.840 --> 52:00.720
Usually people go to the jail and take their doctor with them and give their name and address.

52:00.800 --> 52:08.560
Yes, but yes, I can help you for a little money, perhaps.

52:09.840 --> 52:11.600
Oh, thank you.

52:12.960 --> 52:19.520
Gertrude said. It's better like this. I don't want people to know about it.

52:20.880 --> 52:23.360
Don't want your lover to know, eh?

52:24.560 --> 52:26.400
No. Husband.

52:27.280 --> 52:32.720
Uh-huh. Very well. You can touch the body.

52:35.840 --> 52:39.680
Where is it now? She said, shivering.

52:41.120 --> 52:51.600
It? He, you mean? He's still alive tonight. He's in the jail. A little room right at the top.

52:52.240 --> 52:57.440
And, what must I do tomorrow? Gertrude said.

52:58.720 --> 53:07.360
There's a little door at the back of the jail. Be there at one o'clock. No later.

53:08.400 --> 53:16.560
I can open the door from inside and can take you to the body when they bring him in.

53:16.560 --> 53:29.200
Good night. Don't be late. And you don't want people to see you. So cover your face. Good night, my pretty.

53:32.320 --> 53:36.560
Gertrude went away and walked up to the jail on the hill.

53:38.320 --> 53:43.120
She wanted to find the little door at the back to know it for tomorrow.

53:43.920 --> 53:52.880
Then she went back down into the town and went to her room and waited for the morning.

53:52.880 --> 54:10.000
The

54:10.000 --> 54:13.120
Chapter 6 The Blood Turns

54:13.120 --> 54:22.800
At half past 12 on Saturday, Gertrude Lodge walked up the hill to the jail.

54:24.880 --> 54:31.200
She went there by the small back streets because there were so many people in the town.

54:32.800 --> 54:36.720
They were there for a holiday to watch the hanging.

54:37.360 --> 54:42.320
At one o'clock, she was inside the jail.

54:44.560 --> 54:48.480
The hangman took her to a long, dark room with a table.

54:50.320 --> 54:56.000
Wait there. He told her, two or three minutes, no more.

54:58.880 --> 55:02.000
He went away and Gertrude waited.

55:02.800 --> 55:10.320
She had a veil over her face and her left arm was uncovered, ready.

55:12.160 --> 55:19.920
She stood still with her eyes closed, listening and shivering with terror.

55:22.240 --> 55:28.160
Soon she heard noises and could hear heavy feet on the stairs.

55:28.400 --> 55:38.080
The heavy feet came nearer and four men came into the room with a long box.

55:39.840 --> 55:48.720
It was open and in it was the body of a young man with a cover over his face.

55:51.040 --> 55:53.440
The men put the box down on the table.

55:54.080 --> 55:59.840
Now, said a voice in Gertrude's ear. Now!

56:01.920 --> 56:09.520
But the young woman was half dead with terror and at first she could not move.

56:11.920 --> 56:17.120
Then she opened her eyes and came up to the table.

56:17.120 --> 56:25.840
She could hear other noises outside the room and there were more people coming.

56:28.320 --> 56:31.840
Davis, the hangman, was by her side.

56:33.600 --> 56:43.120
He uncovered the body's face, took Gertrude's hand and put her arm across the dead man's neck.

56:44.000 --> 56:57.280
Gertrude screamed and at once there was a second scream, a woman's scream, but not Gertrude's.

56:59.200 --> 57:01.200
Gertrude turned round.

57:02.880 --> 57:11.440
Behind her stood Rhoda Brooke, her face pale and her eyes red with crying.

57:13.200 --> 57:26.000
Behind Rhoda stood Gertrude's husband. He looked old and sad but there were no tears in his eyes.

57:28.160 --> 57:36.400
You! What in God's name are you doing here? He whispered angrily.

57:37.040 --> 57:42.960
Oh cruel, cruel woman! cried Rhoda.

57:44.560 --> 57:48.720
Why do you come between us and our child now?

57:50.240 --> 57:58.720
This is the true meaning of my dream. You are like that cruel phantom at last.

57:59.520 --> 58:11.840
When Gertrude saw her husband with Rhoda, she knew at once that the dead young man was Rhoda's son.

58:13.760 --> 58:18.000
She stared at Rhoda with terror in her eyes.

58:20.160 --> 58:28.560
Then Rhoda ran to Gertrude, closed her hand round the younger woman's arm and pulled her

58:28.720 --> 58:39.360
away from the table. When she let go of the arm, the young wife fell down at her husband's feet.

58:42.240 --> 58:44.720
She never opened her eyes again.

58:47.200 --> 58:55.120
They carried her out of the jail into the town, but she never got home alive.

58:56.080 --> 59:05.840
Perhaps it was the turning of the blood. Perhaps it was her withered arm.

59:07.040 --> 59:16.160
Perhaps it was her terror in the jail when she turned and saw Rhoda behind her.

59:16.800 --> 59:24.400
Doctors came and looked at her, but they could do nothing to help her.

59:25.600 --> 59:29.920
And three days later, she died.

59:31.520 --> 59:41.360
In those days, the unhappy parents of a hanged man came and took the body away after the hanging.

59:41.520 --> 59:49.920
After the hanging. That was why Farmer Lodge was at the jail with Rhoda that day.

59:52.000 --> 01:00:03.280
It was not his first visit to the jail. With Rhoda, he went many times to visit his son that summer.

01:00:04.720 --> 01:00:09.200
And that was why he was away from the farm so often.

01:00:12.240 --> 01:00:21.040
But after his young wife died, nobody ever saw Farmer Lodge in Casterbridge again.

01:00:23.200 --> 01:00:28.160
He went home to his farm, but he did not stay there long.

01:00:30.000 --> 01:00:39.840
After a short time, he sold the farm and the farmhouse and all the cows and sheep and horses.

01:00:41.760 --> 01:00:53.120
Then he went away to live in a small town by the sea. He lived very quietly, without any friends or

01:00:53.120 --> 01:01:05.360
family near him. When he died two years later, he left a lot of money. Most of it went to a home

01:01:05.360 --> 01:01:10.640
for poor boys. But there was money for Rhoda Brook too.

01:01:13.200 --> 01:01:16.720
For some time, nobody could find Rhoda.

01:01:19.200 --> 01:01:24.240
Then one day, she came back to her old house near the dairy.

01:01:26.640 --> 01:01:30.560
But she never took a penny of Farmer Lodge's money.

01:01:31.360 --> 01:01:39.360
She went back to work in the dairy and worked there for many long years,

01:01:40.480 --> 01:01:45.840
milking the cows in the morning and again in the evening.

01:01:47.840 --> 01:01:56.400
Her dark hair turned white and her sad pale face looked thin and old.

01:01:57.120 --> 01:02:05.600
Most people knew Rhoda's story, and sometimes they watched her at milking time.

01:02:06.800 --> 01:02:15.600
What did she think about? All those long days at morning and evening milking.

01:02:17.200 --> 01:02:19.600
But nobody ever asked her.

01:02:20.960 --> 01:02:24.400
And nobody ever knew the answer.

